Part I - Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Ganiyat Issa-Onilu¶

Introduction¶

This dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

  • Only two columns (Occupation and DebtToIncomeRatio) have missing values.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The original dataset contains 113,937 entries (rows) and 81 features (columns). However, after assessing and cleaning the data, it now contains 84853 entries and 16 features. The features consist of 1 boolean, 1 integer, 5 float, 8 object and 1 datetime data types.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

My main features of interest in the data are:

  • Distribution of loan characteristics .
  • The main factors affecting borrowers' risk score and annual percentage rate.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features that will help support my exploration are: ListingCreationDate, LoanStatus, BorrowerAPR, ProsperScore, BorrowerState, Occupation, EmploymentStatus,IsBorrowerHomeowner, DebtToIncomeRatio, ProsperRating (Alpha), IncomeRange etc.

In this section, I would be carrying out univariate explorations on the BorrowerAPR, ProsperScore, EmploymentStatus, LoanStatus, IncomeRange, ProsperRating (Alpha) and DebtToIncomeRatio columns.

In [21]:
#plot histogram of BorrowerAPR
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
binsize = 0.01
bins = np.arange(0, loan_data['BorrowerAPR'].max()+0.05, binsize)
plt.hist(data = loan_data, x = 'BorrowerAPR', bins = bins)
plt.xlabel("Borrower's APR (%)")
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title("Distribution of Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate")
plt.xlim(0,0.5);

Interpretation: The figure above shows the distribution of annual percentage rate of borrowers. Borrower's APR take on a small range of values between 0.05 and 0.45. The distribution looks unimodal with the largest peak between 0.35 and 0.36. Only very few loans have APR greater than 0.43.

#order income ranges and convert to ordinal data type

                                                categories = ordered_income)
loan_data['IncomeRange'] = loan_data['IncomeRange'].astype(ordered_var)

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x=x, y=y, color=default_color)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 35)

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The borrower's APR is highly influenced by the borrower's prosper rating and income range. We can infer that when the rating and income range is higher, the APR is lower and vice versa. In other words, borrowers with AA prosper ratings should anticipate an APR that will probably fall between 2-25%, while those with poor ratings (HR) can anticipate APR as high as 40%!. Additionally, borrowers with income range of 100,000+ dollars should anticipate a mean APR of 20% while those with an income range of 0 dollar should anticipate mean APR of 30%

What is the effect of Prosper Rating and Loan Terms on Borrower's APR?¶

In [53]:
#plot pointplot 
fig = plt.figure(figsize = [10,6])

plt.ylabel('Borrower APR (%)')
plt.title("Effect of Prosper Rating and Loan Terms on Borrower's APR");

It can be identified that higher prosper ratings are associated with lower borrower's APR. Additionally, for higher grades such as A and AA, the APR tend to increase with longer loan terms compared with that of the lower ratings (such as C and D).

What is the effect of Borrower's employment status and loan status on Borrower's APR?¶

In [54]:
#plot pointplot 
fig = plt.figure(figsize = [10,6])

It can be identified that the unemployed borrowers (regardless of loan status) have higher APR compared to employed and full-time borrowers. Also, the employed and full-time borrowers that have either completed their loan payment or have the final payment in progress tend to have lower APR (%).

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

It can be identified that higher prosper ratings are associated with lower borrower's APR. That is, loans with prosper rating of AA should have the lowest range of Annual Percentage Rates (APRs) of borrowers while loans with rating of HR should have the highest range of APRs

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The multivariate exploration revealed that both higher income ranges and owning a home (that serve as collateral) are stringent requirements that affect the borrower's annual percentage rate.

Conclusions¶

Reflection: This exploratory part of the project involved assessing and cleaning the data before performing data exploration. The exploration included:

  1. Univariate analysis to investigate distribution of feature(s) of interest.
  2. Bivariate analysis to investigate different relationships between two variables.
  3. Multivariate analysis to investigate relationships among three or more variables.

Summary of Findings: From the exploratory analysis, it was discovered that:

  • The main factors associated with the Borrower's APR related to original loan amount are: borrower's income range, prosper rating, collateral and prosper risk score.
  • The unemployed borrowers (regardless of loan status) have higher APR compared to employed and full-time borrowers. On the other hand, the employed and full-time borrowers that have either completed their loan payment or have the final payment in progress tend to have lower APR (%).
